00:01:17.530 --> 00:01:20.890
Both of the options I've got on the table
should do an excellent job of dropping your

00:01:20.890 --> 00:01:25.689
60ft times, and reducing wheel hop and axle
deflection, while increasing your rear end

00:01:25.689 --> 00:01:30.009
group by using superior materials compared
to your factory control arms.

00:01:30.009 --> 00:01:34.619
The non adjustables here feature a strong
TIG welded steel construction, along with

00:01:34.619 --> 00:01:37.770
these polyurethane bushings which are greasable.

00:01:37.770 --> 00:01:42.080
Poly bushings will do a great job of reducing
any noise vibrations or harshness, that you

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:46.740
otherwise might find on the spherical bearings
found on the adjustable control arms here.

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:50.530
In my opinion this is a great option for someone
who enjoys doing some spirited driving with

00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:54.520
their Mustang, maybe just a few track days,
and just wants to replace those soft rubber

00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:56.990
factory bushings in the control arm.

00:01:56.990 --> 00:02:01.179
The adjustable option from SR Performance
is for someone who is serious about their

00:02:01.179 --> 00:02:05.740
track performance, and would ultimately like
to dial in their optimum pinion angle settings.

00:02:05.740 --> 00:02:10.840
For only a few bucks more compared to the
non-adjustables, you're getting full on car

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:16.270
adjustability, strong TIG welded steel construction,
and these spherical hind joints here, which

00:02:16.270 --> 00:02:20.000
are going to take all the unwanted movement
out of your Mustang's rear end.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.819
Both options aren't terribly difficult to
install and should only take you a couple

00:02:23.819 --> 00:02:26.640
of hours in the garage using some pretty basic
hand tools.

00:02:26.640 --> 00:02:30.780
Whenever you switch out your rear upper control
arms I recommend getting your pinion angle

00:02:30.780 --> 00:02:34.750
checked out just to make sure everything's
within spec, especially if you decide to go

00:02:34.750 --> 00:02:35.750
with the adjustables.

00:02:35.750 --> 00:02:40.989
An incorrect pinion angle can cause unwanted
traction, wear and tear on your pinion bearing

00:02:40.989 --> 00:02:42.600
and drive train vibrations.

